Here is an example of a C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

```
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

using namespace std;

int main()
{
    // Declare variables
    string word;
    int count = 0;
    ifstream file;
    string line;

    // Open the text file
    file.open("textfile.txt");
    if (file.fail())
    {
        cout << "Could not open the text file" << endl;
        return 1;
    }

    // Read each line of the text file
    while (getline(file, line))
    {
        // Extract the word from the line
        istringstream ss(line);
        ss >> word;
        if (word == "car")
        {
            count++;
        }
    }
    file.close();

    // Print the number of occurrences of the word "car"
    cout << "Number of occurrences of the word 'car' in the text file: " << count << endl;

    return 0;
}
```

In this program, we declare three variables: `word`, `count`, and `file`. `word` is the specific word we want to count, `count` is the variable that will keep track of the number of occurrences of `word` in the file, and `file` is an `ifstream` object that opens the text file and reads each line.

In the `main` function, we first open the text file and check if the operation was successful. If not, we print an error message and exit the program.

Once the text file is opened, we enter an infinite loop that will read each line of the text file. In the loop, we extract the word from each line using an `istringstream` object. If the word is equal to "car", we increment the value of `count`.

After the loop, we close the file and print the number of occurrences of the word "car" in the text file.

This program reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file.

